texts.html: Darren Barker finally got the world title he's spent an entire career chasing, surviving a knockdown to come back and take the IBF middleweight belt from champion Daniel Geale by split decision in a non-stop action fight Saturday night at the Revel Casino in Atlantic City.
text: Darren Barker finally got the world title he's spent an entire career chasing, surviving a knockdown to come back and take the IBF middleweight belt from champion Daniel Geale by split decision in a non-stop action fight Saturday night at the Revel Casino in Atlantic City.

texts.html: The 31-year-old Barker (26-1, 16 KOs) started strong, winning several of the early rounds by outworking Geale, the Australian by way of Germany. But Geale finally got to the tough Brit in the sixth round.
text: The 31-year-old Barker (26-1, 16 KOs) started strong, winning several of the early rounds by outworking Geale, the Australian by way of Germany. But Geale finally got to the tough Brit in the sixth round.

texts.html: Barker went down from a powerful, paralyzing  body shot from Geale and nearly didn't make the 10 count. But he got up just in time and amazingly came back strong to hurt Geale near the end of the round.
text: Barker went down from a powerful, paralyzing  body shot from Geale and nearly didn't make the 10 count. But he got up just in time and amazingly came back strong to hurt Geale near the end of the round.

texts.html: Barker kept it up much of the rest of the way and finished by landing 292 punches to Geale's 259. Barker also threw nearly 200 more punches. He landed 244 power punches to 211 by Geale (29-2, 15 KOs).
text: Barker kept it up much of the rest of the way and finished by landing 292 punches to Geale's 259. Barker also threw nearly 200 more punches. He landed 244 power punches to 211 by Geale (29-2, 15 KOs).

texts.html: Judges Carlos Ortiz Jr. (114-112) and Barbara Perez (116-111) both scored it for Barker, while Alan Rubenstein had it 114-113 for Geale.
text: Judges Carlos Ortiz Jr. (114-112) and Barbara Perez (116-111) both scored it for Barker, while Alan Rubenstein had it 114-113 for Geale.

texts.html: Barker leapt for joy after being named the winner on the two judges' scorecards.
text: Barker leapt for joy after being named the winner on the two judges' scorecards.

texts.html: "It's so difficult. Nobody really knows the journey I've been through," said Barker, whose only career loss was to middleweight champion Sergio Martinez nearly two years ago, also in Atlantic City. "It's been a real Rocky story, but I've dedicated this to my late brother. Everything I've done is for him."

story, but I've dedicated this to my late brother. Everything I've done is for him."

texts.html: Barker, bloodied and swollen afterwards, was asked how he survived the body punch in the sixth that dropped him.
text: Barker, bloodied and swollen afterwards, was asked how he survived the body punch in the sixth that dropped him.

texts.html: "I take my hat off to Daniel Geale. He's a great champion and a great man. He caught me right on the solar plexus and completely took my breath away," Barker said.
text: "I take my hat off to Daniel Geale. He's a great champion and a great man. He caught me right on the solar plexus and completely took my breath away," Barker said.

texts.html: "But the only thought that went through my head was my late brother and the rest of my family, everyone who stuck by me. They pulled me through it. Without them I couldn't do anything."
text: "But the only thought that went through my head was my late brother and the rest of my family, everyone who stuck by me. They pulled me through it. Without them I couldn't do anything."

texts.html: Geale, 32, who was making the fifth defense of his IBF title, was disappointed by the loss.
text: Geale, 32, who was making the fifth defense of his IBF title, was disappointed by the loss.

texts.html: "I'm not going to whinee and cry and carry on," he said. "Things didn't go my way tonight. I'm very, very disappointed. I worked so hard for that, put everything into that, I did everything I needed to do. I pushed him so hard, I hurt him. But that's what happens.
text: "I'm not going to whinee and cry and carry on," he said. "Things didn't go my way tonight. I'm very, very disappointed. I worked so hard for that, put everything into that, I did everything I needed to do. I pushed him so hard, I hurt him. But that's what happens.

texts.html: "It was a close fight. I'm very disappointed."
text: "It was a close fight. I'm very disappointed."

texts.html: Asked who he wanted to fight next, Barker said, "I just want to go home and see my daughter. I miss her badly.
text: Asked who he wanted to fight next, Barker said, "I just want to go home and see my daughter. I miss her badly.

texts.html: "But before I do that there might be a couple of beers consumed."
text: "But before I do that there might be a couple of beers consumed."

texts.html: In the co-feature, Spain's Kiko Martinez used a relentless, aggressive attack to upset IBF super-bantamweight champion Jhonatan Romero of Colombia with a sixth-round TKO.
text: In the co-feature, Spain's Kiko Martinez used a relentless, aggressive attack to upset IBF super-bantamweight champion Jhonatan Romero of Colombia with a sixth-round TKO.

texts.html: Referee David Fields stopped the fight at 2:40 with a defenseless Romero (23-1) pinned in a neutral corner and absorbing a beating. Martinez (29-4) dropped to his knees in the center of the ring and began to sob while his cornermen hugged him.
text: Referee David Fields stopped the fight at 2:40 with a defenseless Romero (23-1) pinned in a neutral corner and absorbing a beating. Martinez (29-4) dropped to his knees in the center of the ring and began to sob while his cornermen hugged him.

texts.html: "This is a dream for me," Martinez said through a translator. "(HBO ring announcer) Michael Buffer called out my name (as the new champion). This is a dream. I am so happy. I have no words. Today is a marvelous day. We're going to have a big party when I get back home."
text: "This is a dream for me," Martinez said through a translator. "(HBO ring announcer) Michael Buffer called out my name (as the new champion). This is a dream. I am so happy. I have no words. Today is a marvelous day. We're going to have a big party when I get back home."

texts.html: Martinez, who is managed by WBC middleweight champion Sergio Martinez (no relation), took control at the outset of the bout and never relinquished it. In the sixth, he rocked Romero with a left hook and right hook early in the round, then unleashed a bevy of punishing blows that left Romero staggering along the ropes. Romero briefly tried to fight back, but was soon overwhelmed. Martinez pinned him in a neutral corner and continued to fire punches until Fields wisely stepped in.

texts.html: "I just kept throwing punches," Martinez said. "I had to keep the attack on and I knew the referee was going eventually going to have to stop the fight."
text: "I just kept throwing punches," Martinez said. "I had to keep the attack on and I knew the referee was going eventually going to have to stop the fight."

texts.html: Romero was making his first title defense. He won the belt last February, when he gained a 12-round, split decision over Alejandro Lopez in Lopez's hometown of Tijuana, Mexico.
